entry.title: [Gardener] Revert "[base] Integrate (Sequenced|SingleThread)TaskRunner::GetCurrentDefault with RunOrPostTask."
entry.content:
This reverts commit aa9fbff84283de17fe0ee59c28c9edd50b7e6d3a.



Reason for revert: suspected to cause persistent failures in ToolbarControllerUiTest.DeactivatedActionItemsOverflow on https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chrome/builders/ci/win-arm64-rel-ready.



First failing build: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chrome/builders/ci/win-arm64-rel-ready/18427/test-results



Sample output:

https://chrome-swarming.appspot.com/task?id=676f0f21d35f4f11&o=true&w=true



The failure stack has a bunch of scheduling and sequence-related things, ending with ui::test::internal::InteractiveTestPrivate::OnSequenceAborted(). There were only three CLs in the blamelist, and the other two seemed much less likely to be related.



Original change's description:

> [base] Integrate (Sequenced|SingleThread)TaskRunner::GetCurrentDefault with RunOrPostTask.

>

> Within a RunOrPostTask callback running synchronously:

>

> - There is no "current default SingleThreadTaskRunner".

>

> A RunOrPostTask() callback cannot make assumptions about the thread

> on which it runs, so it shouldn't access the current default

> SingleThreadTaskRunner.

>

> - The "current default SequencedTaskRunner" is the SequenceManager's

> default task runner.

>

> A RunOrPostTask() callback runs in sequence with tasks from the

> target SequenceManager. It's appropriate for it to access the

> "current default" SequencedTaskRunner.

>

> Also, with this CL, when

> SingleThreadTaskRunner::BelongsToCurrentThread() is invoked on a

> task runner that runs tasks posted to it "in sequence" with the

> current RunOrPostTask callback running synchronously, but on

> a different thread, it returns `false`. In the same context,

> SingleThreadTaskRunner::RunsTasksInCurrentSequence() returns true.

>

around.

entry.title: [base] Integrate (Sequenced|SingleThread)TaskRunner::GetCurrentDefault with RunOrPostTask.
entry.content:
Within a RunOrPostTask callback running synchronously:



- There is no "current default SingleThreadTaskRunner".



A RunOrPostTask() callback cannot make assumptions about the thread

on which it runs, so it shouldn't access the current default

SingleThreadTaskRunner.



- The "current default SequencedTaskRunner" is the SequenceManager's

default task runner.



A RunOrPostTask() callback runs in sequence with tasks from the

target SequenceManager. It's appropriate for it to access the

"current default" SequencedTaskRunner.



Also, with this CL, when

SingleThreadTaskRunner::BelongsToCurrentThread() is invoked on a

task runner that runs tasks posted to it "in sequence" with the

current RunOrPostTask callback running synchronously, but on

a different thread, it returns `false`. In the same context,

SingleThreadTaskRunner::RunsTasksInCurrentSequence() returns true.

entry.title: Fix crash when auctionNonce on auction config is not a valid UUIDv4.
entry.content:
Before this change, providing an auctionNonce that's not a valid UUIDv4

would crash the page. The conversion from the string auctionNonce in the

auctionConfig IDL to the UUID auctionNonce in the auctionConfig mojo message

had previously assumed that the "empty" UUID that results from failing

to parse an invalid auctionNonce would reach the AuctionNonceManager,

where it would be rejected, since it could not have been produced by a

previous call to `navigator.createAuctionNonce()`. However, mojo fails

to deserialize the empty UUID, causing a crash before it ever reached

the AuctionNonceManager.



This change adds an explicit validity check, and throws an appropriate

error when a malformed auctionNonce is provided.

entry.title: Don't run address cleanups on stale data
entry.content:
Address cleanups wait until sync is ready, but potentially are still

performed too early if the PDM hasn't finished reloading the new data

from the database yet. This CL fixes this by waiting for

OnPersonalDataFinishedProfileTasks() after sync is ready.



It does so by decoupling the PDM from AddressDataCleaner (ADC):

- Instead of calling the ADC in various places in the PDM, the ADC

becomes a PDMObserver and a SyncServiceObserver.

- In PDMObserver::OnPersonalDataFinishedProfileTasks()

MaybeCleanupAddressData() is called. For non syncing users, this

continues to cause the deduplication to happen after the initial

load.

For syncing users, MaybeCleanupAddressData() will ignore this call,

since sync is not ready yet. In this case, the OnStateChanged() event

will later inform the ADC that sync is ready. There, this CL adds

logic to determine if the PDM is currently waiting for reads. If so

the cleanups is delayed until the next

OnPersonalDataFinishedProfileTasks().

entry.title: [Device Posture] Move device posture implementation out of services/
entry.content:
It's becoming clear that the posture is not a global state. On Android

the posture is tied to an Activity : for example an Android Activity can

be on an external screen or two Chrome instances side by side and Android does not return the physical posture of the device. While right now Windows is a global state we can imagine scenarios like this where the "logical" posture doesn't match the physical posture.



This patch moves the device_posture mojo implementation out of services/. This means that now it is attached to a given web content. This allows us to simplify some of the implementation now that we can assume the receivers are from the same web content.



Also now that we are in the content/ layer we can directly hook into the device posture classes to implement the viewport segments support in RWHA.

- Merges AddressDataCleaner::MaybeCleanupAddressData()

MaybeCleanupAddressDataAfterSyncChange() to a single

MaybeCleanupAddressData(sync_service).

This function is called after the PDM's initial load has finished and

again in PDM::OnStateChanged() (SyncServiceObserver implementation).

- MaybeCleanupAddressData(sync_service) determines whether the code

should wait for sync based on the sync_service. It further ensures

that clean-ups are called at most once (since OnStateChanged() might

be called many times).



This CL doesn't yet fix the problem that deduplication likely runs too

early after sync has started: After changes were synced down, they are

written to AutofillTable - the PDM needs to asynchronously reload them

before the cleanup logic can use it. This has likely not finished yet by

the time OnStateChanged() is called.

A follow-up CL will take care of this.

entry.title: Copy FormData::child_frames_ into FormStructure.
entry.content:
This field is used in `FormData::DeepEqual`, and in

`BrowserAutofillManager::ShouldTriggerRefill` this method is

called with a `FormData` recreated from a `FormStructure`.

Loosing this property leads to constant `false` from the `DeepEqual`

method and unnecessarily scheduled refilling for pages with iframes.



In this CL crrev.com/c/5036442 the refill triggering logic was moved

from the renderer to browser process. The same `DeepEqual` was used,

but it worked with `FormData` directly, while now it is converted from

`FormStructure` (where the `child_frames` field was missing).



It partially fixes the associated ticket by reducing the number of

events by a factor of 2.

entry.title: [URL] Support non-special URLs in Resolve()
entry.content:
Implement correct support for non-special URLs in gurl::Resolve() and

other functions, which are used on resolving a relative URL on a given

base URL.



Example:



Prior to this change:



> new URL("path", "git://host/") => throws an invalid URL error



After this change:



> new URL("path", "git://host/") => "git://host/path""



The feature is currently guarded by the flag.



This CL adds several parameterized unit tests to test flag-dependent

behaviors. Currently flag-independent behaviors are not tested with

the flag. I will revisit this later.



Though this CL introduces new expectation files for virtual tests,

there is no regression and the total number of test failures has

decreased. I use rebaseline cl tool and accept the result as is. It

seems there are several expectation files across different platforms,

accumulated over time.
